Part I - Airline On-Time Performance Data for Summer 2022¶

by Manon Mason¶

Introduction¶

This document explores a dataset containing performance information for approximately two million US domestic flights during peak summer travel - from June to September - for the year 2022.

This exploration aims to study the flight delays and cancellations over this period.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 2 319 544 flights in this dataset with 23 features.

  • Year: Year data collected. In our dataset, the year will be 2022.
  • Month: Numeric representation of the month. 6: June, 7: July, 8: August, 9: September.
  • Day_Of_Week: Numeric representation of the day of the week. 1: Monday, 2:Tuesday, 3: Wednesday, 4: Thursday, 5: Friday, 6: Saturday, 7: Sunday.
  • Fl_Date: Date of the flight
  • Origin: Origin Airport
  • Origin_City_Name: Origin Airport, City Name
  • Origin_State_Abr: Origin State Abbreviation
  • Dest: Destination Airport
  • Dest_City_Name: Destination Airport, City Name
  • Crs_Dep_Time: CRS Departure Time (local time: hhmm). CRS is Computer Reservation System. It provides information on airline schedules, fares and seat availability to travel agencies and allow agents to book seats and issue ticket.
  • Arr_Time: Actual Arrival Time (local time: hhmm)
  • Arr_Delay: Difference in minutes between scheduled and actual arrival time. Early arrivals show negative numbers.
  • Arr_Delay_New: Difference in minutes between scheduled and actual arrival time. Early arrivals set to 0.
  • Arr_Del15: Arrival Delay Indicator, 15 Minutes or More. 1: Yes, 0: No
  • Cancelled: Cancelled Flight Indicator. 1: Yes, 0: No
  • Cancellation_Code: Specifies the reason for cancellation. A: Carrier, B: Weather, C: National Air System, D: Security)
  • Air_Time: Flight time, in minutes
  • Distance: Distance between airports (miles)
  • Carrier_Delay: Carrier delay, in minutes
  • NAS_Delay: National Air System Delay, in minutes
  • Security_Delay: Security delay, in minutes
  • Late_Aircraft_Delay: Late aircraft delay, in minutes

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in the flights canceled or delayed over the summer of 2022. I am hoping that by studying this data, some features will emerge to help predict when and where delays and cancelations are most likely to happen.

between June and September 2022, and if there are any pattern that stands out (day of the week, airport, destination).

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that the distance between airports, the time of departure, and the carrier play a role in the flights' s performance.

There are 51522 canceled flights in the data frame. However, we notice some discrepancies when printing the null values for each column.

We have 51931 null values for the ARR_TIME column, so there is a difference of 409 rows. We have 57895 null values for ARR_DELAY, ARR_DELAY_NEW, ARRDEL15, and AIR_TIME, so a difference of 6373 rows.

If the flight wasn't canceled, those values should be known, so it looks like we are missing some data.

Now, looking at those 6373 missing values, we are here, too, missing crucial flight information. We do not know anything about their performances (whether they were delayed, for how long, and why). Since we are most interested in this, and there is no way to infer that information, I will drop those rows.

CLEANING¶

I have assembled a list of cleaning tasks through visual and programmatic assessments. Once those steps are completed, plotting visualizations will be easier.

  • Change certain columns type. FL_TIME needs to be a date time object. YEAR a string. DAY_OF_WEEK, MONTH, CANCELLATION_CODE, ARR_DEL15, CANCELLED, into a category, DISTANCE into an integer.
  • The current OP_UNIQUE_CARRIER variable is impractical; we do not know the airline the code refers to. The reference exists in a separate dataframe called "unique_carrier_code". Merge this second dataframe with our main one to have the reference on hand.
  • Drop the rows where we found missing values.
  • Replace 0.0 with null values for CARRIER_DELAY, WEATHER_DELAY, NAS_DELAY SECURITY_DELAY, LATE_AIRCRAFT_DELAY columns.
  • Fill the null values for 'AIR_TIME' with 0 and change the type from float to int.
  • Modify CRS_DEP_TIME and ARR_TIME so the float values read 00:00, for hours and minutes.
  • Create a new column that separate the hours into four categories: Morning, Afternoon, Evening and Night.
  • Replace the 0.0 values with null values in ARR_DELAY_NEW.

'''Define a function that take the name of a dataframe, the column we wish to change the type to category, 
the list of the categories, and whether or not you want the categories to be ordered.'''
def cat_type(df, column, categories, ordered):
    df[column] =  pd.Categorical(df[column], categories=categories, ordered=ordered)

Define

  • Turn 'ARR_DEL15' and 'CANCELLED' into categories.

First we need to change them to string. Then using string slicing, we want to extract '1' from 1.0 and '0' from 0.0. In the process 'NaN' will turn into 'n'. Then, we need to turn strings into category using pd.Categorical.

Code

In [33]:
#Create a function that will turn an integer intro string and then slice the string to only keep the first character.
def to_string(df):
    return df.astype('str').str[:-2]
In [34]:
#apply the to_string function to ARR_DEL15 and CANCELLED
flight_copy[['ARR_DEL15', 'CANCELLED']] = flight_copy[['ARR_DEL15', 'CANCELLED']].apply(to_string)

Univariate Exploration¶

I will start by exploring the variables of interest one by one, beginning with the cancellation codes.

What were the main reasons for flight cancellation over the summer of 2022?

A: Carrier
B: Weather
C: National Air System
D: Security

Which delay was most frequent? And which one caused longer delays?

To create a bar plot of the different delays, we need to take a few steps.

  • We need two lists, one for the heights of the bar and one for the labels.
  • To get those lists, we will create an empty dictionary to store the delay's names and counts.
  • After looping through each delay, we will store its name and count in the dictionary.
  • For the bar heights, we will use the dictionary's keys and the dictionary's values for the labels.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

We discovered that the ARR_DELAY variable took an extensive range of values, skewing the data heavily to the right. Delays were sometimes as small as 5 minutes and sometimes as long as a day or more.

Since delayed flights are the main point of interest, I isolated them and created a separate subset of the data frame called subset_late. Because of the outliers, I created an histogram of the ARR_DELAY variable, using a log transformation on the x-axis.

Under this log transformation, the data looked unimodal, with a peak around 20 minutes and another small one under 5 minutes.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

While investigating the arr_delay variable, we noticed significant positive outliers and the mode before zero, meaning that many flights were actually early.

The wide range of data points made it difficult to read, so I separated the data into three subsets: one for the early flights, one for the flights that were on time, and one for the delayed flights. I created a bar chart with a bar for each subset, making it easy to compare each subset. This method showed me that more flights have left early than late. Although this was a notable find, I am still only interested in flights that have been canceled or delayed.

Looking at the different delays, I wanted to compare them to another. To do so, I looped through each delay and saved their names and counts into a dictionary. I used this dictionary to create a bar plot showing the count of each delay next to the other. Another option could have been to use the pd.melt() function on the data frame to reshape the data and create a more general 'Delay' column, but that would have added a lot more rows to an already large data frame, so I decided not to follow this route.

Through this bar chart, we found out that Carrier and Late Aircraft were the most common delays. The Weather didn't cause many delays, probably because the airline chose to cancel rather than delay flights when the Weather was extreme, Weather being the main reason for canceled flights.

To make the delay variable easier to read - especially the negative values, which are the flights that have departed early - I have decided to separate the ARR_DELAY variable into bins: flights that are Over an Hour Early, 30 to 60 minutes early, Less than 30 minutes early, On Time, Less than an hour late, 1 to 2 hours late, 2 to 4 hours late, 4 to 8 hours late, 8 to 12 hours late, 12 to 24 hours late, and Over 24 hours late.

Once separated into bins, I will compare those to the distance variable.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Weather delays were an average an hour long, although they happened less frequently than other delays. It is also the main reason for cancellation for most airlines.

On average, the airlines with the most prolonged delays were Mesa Airlines, Endeavor Air, and Skywest. The airlines with the highest cancellation percentage were Republic Airlines, Endeavor Air, and American Airlines.

The three airlines that performed the best in both categories were Alaska Airlines, Hawaiian Airlines, and Horizon Air.

Flights leaving from and to New Jersey, Maine, New York, and Rhode Island are more likely to be canceled during the summer months. Flights departing from and going to Delaware were delayed by over an hour.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

There is a slight negative correlation between distance and delays: short and medium flights were more susceptible to long delays than long-haul flights. It is interesting because this is unexpected; we would have guessed that longer flights would be more prone to delays.

However, we didn't observe any correlation between cancellation and distance. Longer flights are not more likely to be canceled than shorter flights.

Cancellation happened more often during June and August. Because our dataset consists of 2022 only, the sample is not large enough for us to draw any decisive conclusion concerning the months. We would have to compare those months to other future or past years to see if any pattern exists.

Multivariate Exploration¶

Diving deeper into the delayed and canceled flights.

As seen previously, there is not an even number of flights each day, each hour, each month. Some days and parts of the day have a higher traffic than others. For comparison, we then have to work with percentages rather than numbers. What is the rate of cancellation for a Tuesday vs a Wednesday? Afternoon vs Evening?

Let's look first at the cancellation and delay rate throughout the day. Is a flight most likely to be canceled or delayed at night or in the afternoon?

First, we need to find the number of canceled flights per time period using Groupby.

In [166]:
#Group by time of day and count the CANCELLATION_CODE column to get the number of cancelled flights

Divide the number of canceled flights by the total of flights for each period and multiply by 100 to get the percentage, rounded to two decimals. Save our results under a dataframe.

In [167]:
#Get the percentage of flight rounded to 2 decimals
tod_cancelled = np.round((flight_copy.groupby('TIME_OF_DAY')['CANCELLATION_CODE'].count()\
                          / flight_copy['TIME_OF_DAY'].value_counts()) *100,2)
#Creat a dataframe using reset_index, rename columns for clarity
tod_cancelled = tod_cancelled.reset_index().rename(columns={0: "CANCELLED_PERC"})

As a reminder :

  • Morning: Between 6am and noon
  • Afternoon: Between noon and 6pm
  • Evening: Between 6pm and midnight
  • Night: Between midnight and 6am

Although flights leaving at night suffered the smallest percentage of delays and cancellations, it is an inconvenient time to fly. The next best time is the morning, between 6 am and noon. Almost 50% of the flights leaving in the Evening got delayed, and the Evening also had the highest rate of cancellation, with over 3% of its flights being canceled.

However, this plot does not tell you when the longest delays tend to happen; it just shows that delays occur more frequently in the afternoons and evenings. Most travelers would rather be delayed by 30 minutes than 4 hours, which is not an information we can extract from this visualization.

To get this information, we need to focus on the arr_delay_bins instead, which tells us approximately how long the flight has been delayed. Plotting this with the time of day will give us the period that suffers the longest delays.

Since ARR_DELAY_BINS is an ordinal categorical variable in nature, we will use a pointplot.

We first need to find out the percentage for each delay bins and each time of day.

This plot gives us an overview of how well each airline performs cancellation and delay-wise. Hawaiian Airlines is doing great on cancellations, but over 50% of their flights were delayed. Even though Republic Airlines and Endeavor fare the worst regarding cancellation with 5%, their delay percentage is only about 30%. Our univariate visualization showed that a majority of the flights belonged to Southwest, Delta, and American Airlines. Looking at the three airlines in this graph, Delta is doing the best in both cancellations and delays. Southwest is doing better with cancellations than America, but America is doing better with delays.

Although this is interesting, using a multivariate plot for the cancellation and the delays does not give us any more insight into performance than if we had two separate graphs, one for cancellation and one for delays.

Has the location affected how well the airline is performing? Is there a state where the airline is doing better or worse than others? We can find out by comparing the cancellation and delay rates for each airline and each state. We will use a heatmap since we are working with two categorical variables.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

We found out that afternoon and evening not only have the highest percentage of delays and cancellations, but their delays tend to be longer. Flights departing in the morning or at night tend to arrive earlier. Those trends show us that the departure time correlates to whether a flight will be canceled or delayed.

Some airlines perform better than others; however, cancellations do not correlate with delays. An airline with a high delay percentage doesn't necessarily mean that the cancellation rate is also high and vice versa.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Airlines, states of origin, and delay/cancellation percentages were not correlated. During one of our bivariate analyses, we observed that certain airlines cancel their flights mainly because of the weather. Therefore, I expected them to behave differently depending on where they were departing from, but it does not appear so. This lack of correlation is less surprising when it comes to delay since the two leading causes for delays are Carrier and Late Aircraft, issues that stem from the airline side and its crew and management, unrelated to the airport or the state itself.

Conclusions¶

The main goal of this exploration was to study, through univariate, bivariate, and multivariate visualization, the performance of approximately two million US domestic flights over the summer of 2022. Through this study, we mainly focused on delays and cancellations. The dataset was ready for analysis after a quick visual and programmatic assessment and a light data cleaning. We were interested in highlighting and discovering any pattern that could help identify the variables linked to the delayed or canceled flights.

We started with some univariate visualization that helped us better understand the data and identify the points of interest. We discovered that the weather was the main reason for flight cancellation, and carrier and late aircraft were the main reasons for delays.

We then focused on the bivariate analysis, where we dived deeper into the relationship between delay and cancellation and the other variables. We discovered that the East Coast is home to several states with a high cancellation percentage. Delay-wise, Delaware performs poorly, with delays of an average of 180 minutes. We expected long-haul flights to have longer delays than short-haul hauls, but the data showed us that the opposite is true. Distance is also not correlated to cancellation. Weather is confirmed as causing the longest delays, with over an hour delay on average.

Finally, we looked closely at how the variables interacted with one another through a multivariate analysis. The departure time affects delays, with evening and afternoon having more frequent and longer delays. Although we saw that some states and airlines fare better or worse than others on their own, we could not establish a correlation between delays/cancellations, states, and airlines.

Overall, this dataset was instructive and gave us some fascinating insight into which variables affect flight performance and which don't.
